<div id="review_3002317313" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3002317313" />
    <a title="Edward Lorn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8850418-edward-lorn"><img alt="Edward Lorn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492199506p2/8850418.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3002317313?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward Lorn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward Lorn" href="/user/show/8850418-edward-lorn">Edward Lorn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6637865-every-dead-thing">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3002317313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14832852032975128264">Video review: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://youtu.be/bGCBgemFdoE'>https://youtu.be/bGCBgemFdoE</a><br/><br/>I&apos;ve been returning to books I&apos;ve marked DNF in the past five years and am finding that I&apos;m enjoying more of them than I am not. If I return to one and my opinion hasn&apos;t changed, I&apos;m not updating my review. But in cases like this, I feel the need to tell y&apos;all what happened. <br/><br/>Unfortunately, I don&apos;t recall what I disliked the first time I tried reading this one, and my previous review was unhelpful. It did mention a quote I didn&apos;t care for, but the quote f</span>
  <span id="freeText14832852032975128264" style="display:none">Video review: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/bGCBgemFdoE">https://youtu.be/bGCBgemFdoE</a><br /><br />I've been returning to books I've marked DNF in the past five years and am finding that I'm enjoying more of them than I am not. If I return to one and my opinion hasn't changed, I'm not updating my review. But in cases like this, I feel the need to tell y'all what happened. <br /><br />Unfortunately, I don't recall what I disliked the first time I tried reading this one, and my previous review was unhelpful. It did mention a quote I didn't care for, but the quote failed to concern me this time, so I was able to finish the book. And, boy-who, am I glad I fuckin did.<br /><br />What instigated my return to this one in particular, I hear absolutely no one asking? Well, No One, I decided to give this book another try after Atria Publishing sent me <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41131135.A_Book_of_Bones__Charlie_Parker___17_" title="A Book of Bones (Charlie Parker, #17) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">A Book of Bones</a>, Book 17 in the Connolly's long-running Charlie Parker series, for review. When I expressed concern for starting a series at Book 17, my contact at the publisher sent me Book 16, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35628855.The_Woman_in_the_Woods__Charlie_Parker___16_" title="The Woman in the Woods (Charlie Parker, #16) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">The Woman in the Woods</a>. To be fair, I was told that books 16 and 17 tie directly into one another, and I passed this information along to my contact at Atria, but me being OCD about such things, I think we all knew I wasn't gonna be able to start at Book 16. Sorry, Ariele...the good news is, I'm already two books deep and moving quicker than Cadbury eggs through a diabetic. <br /><br />As of writing this, I am 50 pages from the end of Book 2, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/175243.Dark_Hollow__Charlie_Parker___2_" title="Dark Hollow (Charlie Parker, #2) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">Dark Hollow</a>, and finding myself a John Connolly convert. I'm a huge fan now. I plan on starting Book 3, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/175246.The_Killing_Kind__Charlie_Parker___3_" title="The Killing Kind (Charlie Parker, #3) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">The Killing Kind</a>, as soon as I'm done with Book 2. Yeah, I'm bingeing these bitches like they on Netflix, or some shit. Don't @ me. <br /><br />My favorite characters so far are Louis and Angel. Charlie's great, Rachel is meh, but Angel and Louis are my buddies. I'm happy someone spoiled me by saying they're a mainstay of the series. That's awesome, and the best spoiler I've received in recent memory.<br /><br />In summation: Y'all better be happy with this review because I stopped reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/175243.Dark_Hollow__Charlie_Parker___2_" title="Dark Hollow (Charlie Parker, #2) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">Dark Hollow</a> just to write it. So if y'all'll excuse me, I'm gonna go finish this DARK HOLLOW motherfucker. This first book, though? This one is highly recommended. If you haven't read Connolly, I shall leave you with a quote from my good friend Shane Keene: "Unfuck that post haste."<br /><br /><b>Final Judgment: I change my mind more than you change your underwear, you nasty bastard.</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="14832852032975128264" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

