  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1183351049" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1183351049" />
    <a title="Jean" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28831526-jean"><img alt="Jean" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615997422p2/28831526.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1183351049?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jean" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jean" href="/user/show/28831526-jean">Jean</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1183351049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11550894785305288014">What an intro! When Charlie “Bird” Parker describes the murder of his wife and young daughter in the prologue of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/175242.Every_Dead_Thing__Charlie_Parker___1_' title='Every Dead Thing (Charlie Parker, #1) by John Connolly' rel='nofollow noopener'>Every Dead Thing</a>, I was riveted. At the same time, I was horrified and distressed. This book threatened, or promised, depending upon your reading preferences, to be a gruesome display of serial killings.<br/><br/>I found it to be that and much more. I’d be lying if I said that I enjoyed every moment of it. I especially didn’t enjoy the seemingly endless rivalries between organized crime bosses </span>
  <span id="freeText11550894785305288014" style="display:none">What an intro! When Charlie “Bird” Parker describes the murder of his wife and young daughter in the prologue of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/175242.Every_Dead_Thing__Charlie_Parker___1_" title="Every Dead Thing (Charlie Parker, #1) by John Connolly" rel="nofollow noopener">Every Dead Thing</a>, I was riveted. At the same time, I was horrified and distressed. This book threatened, or promised, depending upon your reading preferences, to be a gruesome display of serial killings.<br /><br />I found it to be that and much more. I’d be lying if I said that I enjoyed every moment of it. I especially didn’t enjoy the seemingly endless rivalries between organized crime bosses vying for superiority by constantly shooting each other. Somehow, Charlie Parker seemed to be in the midst of it all, beginning in New York and winding up in New Orleans. Aside from the ruthless butchering of his wife and child and other victims, which is the main plot, I found the violence excessive. In addition, the number of characters was overwhelming, and since I was reading a print copy, I didn’t have the luxury of a search key. In short, I’d have enjoyed this saga more if Mr. Connolly had trimmed one hundred or more pages of details and descriptions of homicidal events that were unrelated to the search for his family’s killer. The quest for the killer, the “Traveling Man,” would have been enough to satisfy me. My feeling is that the author just tried to do too much with this first of the series, which now stands at fourteen.<br /><br />Parker himself is something of an enigma. Named for jazz saxophonist Charlie Bird Parker, he is a former cop turned private detective. When his wife and child were killed, he quit the police force and stopped drinking. At times I found him unlikable, but as his character developed throughout the course of the book, I began to appreciate his complexity. He is both tough and vulnerable. Although his marriage had been troubled, he had loved his wife, still loved her and missed her and wanted her killer brought to justice. Throughout the novel, he is accompanied by two unlikely sidekicks, Louis and Angel, who both have criminal backgrounds and happen to be gay. They’re a good team, and I rather liked them. There are an assortment of cops and FBI associates, some quite appealing, who tolerate Parker tagging along and poking his nose in where he shouldn’t. <br /><br />Where Parker goes, the body count increases. Despite numerous pages filled with too many gangsters and too many deaths, I found a good deal of excitement and tension as well. What really fascinated me were the supernatural and symbolic elements that were presented by Rachel and by Tante Marie. Even Parker himself touches that dimension a few times. What of the killer? He leaves clues, but in the end, I didn’t get a sense that this demented soul believed anything at all.<br /><br />My overall impression of <i>Every Dead Thing</i> is that it was okay, but it left me disappointed. It had the potential to be spellbinding, but it wandered off course too frequently to the point where I was almost ready to discontinue reading it. I stuck with it, mesmerized at times, gritting my teeth through other sections; two-thirds of the way through it, I had a good hunch as to the identity of the killer. Since I have heard good things about this author and this series, I may be willing to chalk this up to it being a first attempt and give him another shot at some point. <br /><br />3.5 stars<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11550894785305288014" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


